IMF Needs More Lagarde
Davos — Lagarde once said she was open to serving another five years as head of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should stay on.
The IMF has never had a better leadership than her, and the IMF board should give her the opportunity to finish the work she started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, inheriting an institution in crisis.
The 2008 global financial crash and its economic aftermath left Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free-market "Washington Consensus" in disrepute.
Lagarde's leadership helped the IMF restore its reputation.
Many have looked to her personal qualities — rightly so.
She is candid, strong, warm, and compelling.
Officials from various countries (often meeting in delicate circumstances) who have met her have praised her for speaking bluntly about difficult realities while also being a sensitive listener.
These are important qualities for a leader of an institution that must negotiate the terms of an agreement rather than dictate everything.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed to be restructured, or else firewalls had to be established to prevent financial contagion. The advice was unpleasant, but the Europeans complied.
Similarly, she strongly urged providing IMF support to some countries — such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless other examples.
The IMF is not known for innovation and is usually not full of passion.
Lagarde began to change this.
In the process, she gave this institution, which often prescribed harsh remedies, a more humane face.
For example, helping manage the refugee crisis in the Middle East was originally not within the IMF's mandate.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plans to enable the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to assist those displaced by the conflicts in Syria and Iraq (over a million people reside in refugee camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak hit West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF to use its available funds to provide debt relief to countries affected by the crisis, allowing them to improve the pay for doctors and nurses — this was the first time the IMF used its capital in such a way.
Furthermore, Lagarde recognizes that the world today faces three most important challenges and takes actions against them.
First, she strongly calls for more women to join the workforce, and she herself is a role model demonstrating the value of women in leadership positions.
In various countries from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urges leaders to stop wasting such a huge human resource — and thus realize economic potential.
Second, under her leadership, the IMF also addresses the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not just a fundamental issue of fairness.
The IMF's research emphasizes that there is a direct link between reducing the wealth gap and increasing economic growth.
The IMF is not the first institution to prove this, but its position makes the issue more prominent and urgent.
Lagarde personally has been committed to promoting this point, which is key to the increased urgency.
Third, Lagarde has played an important role in helping the world recognize the full impact of technological change — some of which will cause frightening disruptive effects.
For example, automation will continue to increase efficiency in manufacturing and reduce costs, but it also means that the number of jobs generated by economic growth will be less than before.
The political, economic, and social consequences of this emerging reality are worth our understanding and serious study.
Lagarde has made the IMF the core of this effort.
Critics would say it is time for developing countries' representatives to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th European in a row to hold this position, and with such privileges, Europe finds it hard to convince the world today.
Others would say that the austerity measures supported by the IMF in Greece have not yielded sufficient results, proving that she has become detached from the general public.
Others will point out that she faces charges related to a financial scandal in France, which would distract her from her work at the IMF.
After her predecessor, Dominique Strauss-Kahn, was embroiled in a scandal, critics argue that the IMF must never again be distracted by similar events.
Let's examine these objections one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside Europe and the United States.
But the aim of ending this Western privilege is to make the leader selection process based on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best candidate for the IMF's managing director, and the emerging powers such as the BRICS (Brazil, Russia, India and China) have not jointly proposed an alternative candidate.
Having a European serve as the IMF's managing director might also have been a favorable factor in the IMF's decision at the end of last year to include the renminbi in the currency basket that determines the value of its special drawing rights.
Moreover, Lagarde's impressive political flexibility ultimately convinced both the Republican and Democratic parties in the U.S. Congress to approve the IMF governance reforms, which not only enhanced the IMF's arsenal to contain financial crises, but also more accurately reflected the changing dynamics of the global economy.
For example, the BRICS countries have now become among the top ten shareholders of the IMF.
On the Greek issue, Lagarde made some blunt — which some people considered inappropriate — remarks of her own style last year.
But she is certainly not the culprit responsible for the economic suffering of the Greeks. Her tenure at the IMF fully demonstrates that in the history of the IMF, no managing director has done so much to lead the IMF in its efforts to alleviate the suffering of people in crisis.
Finally, the accusations against Lagarde by France were opposed by the French Chief Prosecutor, and Lagarde was at most only slightly involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has proven that she is exactly such a leader, committed to adapting the IMF for the 21st century.
She deserves the opportunity to see things through from start to finish.
